{{Infobox basketball biography | name = Steve Mix | image = Steve Mix 1979.JPG | width = | caption = Mix in 1979 | position = | height_ft = 6 | height_in = 7 | weight_lb = 215 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|12|30}} | birth_place = [[Toledo, Ohio]] | nationality = American | high_school = [[Rogers High School (Toledo, Ohio)|Rogers]] (Toledo, Ohio) | college = [[Toledo Rockets men's basketball|Toledo]] (1966–1969) | draft_year = 1969 | draft_round = 5 | draft_pick = 61 | draft_team = [[Detroit Pistons]] | career_number = 23, 50 | career_position = [[Small forward]] | career_start = 1969 | career_end = 1983 | years1 = {{nbay|1969|start}}–{{nbay|1971|start}} | team1 = [[Detroit Pistons]] | years2 = [[1971–72 ABA season|1971]] | team2 = [[Denver Rockets]] | years3 = {{nbay|1973|start}}–{{nbay|1981|end}} | team3 = [[Philadelphia 76ers]] | years4 = {{nbay|1982|full=y}} | team4 = [[Milwaukee Bucks]] | years5 = {{nbay|1982|end}} | team5 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]] | highlights = * [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|1975}}) * [[Mid-American Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|MAC Player of the Year]] (1969) * 3× First-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (1967–1969) | stats_league = NBA and ABA | stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]] | stat1value = 8,357 (10.6 ppg) | stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]] | stat2value = 4,160 (5.3 rpg) | stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]] | stat3value = 1,393 (1.8 apg) | bbr = mixst01 }} '''Steven Charles Mix''' (born December 30, 1947), nicknamed '''The Mayor''', is an American [[Usher (occupation)|usher]] and former professional [[basketball]] player and coach.
==Basketball career== Mix attended [[Rogers High School (Toledo, Ohio)|Rogers High School]] in [[Toledo, Ohio]], and the [[University of Toledo]].
Mix was a forward with a 13-year career from 1969&ndash;1972 and from 1973&ndash;1983. He played for the [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]], [[Milwaukee Bucks]] and [[Los Angeles Lakers]] all of the NBA and the [[Denver Rockets]] of the [[American Basketball Association|ABA]]. Mix represented the 76ers in the [[1975 NBA All-Star Game]].<ref>http://www.whitehotsports.com/?p=14132{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> Mix made it to the NBA Finals four times overall, three times with the 76ers (1977, 1980, 1982), but never won an NBA title. In 1983, when the 76ers did win the NBA title, Mix was a bench player for the Los Angeles Lakers, who were swept by the 76ers.
Following his retirement as a player, became basketball head coach at his alma mater, the [[University of Toledo]]. In his one year in the position during the 1984-1985 season, the team went 6-20.<ref name=trinetrime>{{cite web|title=Former NBA player to coach Trine women |url=http://www.d3hoops.com/notables/2012/04/former-nba-player-to-coach-trine-women |publisher=D3Hoops.com |accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref> Afterwards, Mix spent 22 years as a [[color commentator]] on the 76ers' television broadcasts.<ref>{{cite web |title=From impersonating Dr. J to coaching D-III, Steve Mix enjoying basketball |url=http://www.csnphilly.com/basketball-philadelphia-sixers/impersonating-dr-j-coaching-d-iii-steve-mix-enjoying-basketball |publisher=CSNPhilly.com |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232110/http://www.csnphilly.com/basketball-philadelphia-sixers/impersonating-dr-j-coaching-d-iii-steve-mix-enjoying-basketball |archivedate=2016-03-03 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, he worked a basketball analyst for [[SportsTime Ohio]]. In 2012, Mix was named women's head coach at [[Trine University]].<ref name=trinetrime /> Mix left his position at Trine in 2014.
Since moving to Florida after his retirement at Trine, Mix has coached at basketball camps at [[Indian River State College]].
==Ushering career== After his retirement from basketball, Mix and his wife moved to [[Vero Beach]], [[Florida]]. After calling [[Detroit Tigers]] clubhouse manager Jim Schmakel, Mix found a job as an usher for the [[New York Mets]] at [[First Data Field]] in nearby [[Port St. Lucie]], where the Mets hold [[Spring Training]] and where two of the Mets' minor-league affiliates, the [[St. Lucie Mets]] and the rookie-league [[Gulf Coast League Mets]], play. Regarding why he took up work as an usher, Mix said: "I heard somebody say sometime, when you retire and you do nothing, how do you know when you are done? I need that place where I can hang my hat. I just need a place where I can do something." Mix has received some recognition from fans who know him from his basketball days, including Mets Special Assistant to the General Manager [[J. P. Ricciardi]], who himself coached high school basketball teams at Holy Name High School in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]], [[Massachusetts]]. Besides Ricciardi, Mix said that a few people recognize him each day: "I have a couple people bring cards up ... probably a couple times a day somebody will say something."<ref name=nypost>{{cite web|title=Why is this ex-NBA star taking tickets at Mets games?|url=https://nypost.com/2017/03/19/why-is-this-ex-nba-star-taking-tickets-at-mets-games/|publisher=New York Post}}</ref>
==Personal life== Mix married his wife, Maryalice, in 1970. They have four children together and reside in [[Vero Beach]], [[Florida]].<ref name=nypost />
During and since their playing days, when they were teammates and roommates, Mix and [[Julius Erving]] have been close friends, calling each other for their birthdays to the present day. Mix was nicknamed "Sky" by Erving; according to Mix, "Julius and [Mix] would talk hoops, [they] would talk life [and] family. Every night [Erving] would have a candy bar before he would go to bed. He used to say, 'I'm calling you [Mix] Sky because you can't.'"<ref name=nypost />
